04900nam a22007095i 9781782048473DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820484737 a10.1515/97817820484732doi  a(DE-B1597)674621  a(OCoLC)1420506761  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a831/.221 aMatthews, Alastair, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Medieval German ‹I›Lohengrin‹/I› :bNarrative Poetics in the Story of the Swan Knight /cAlastair Matthews.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 1bCamden House, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (250 p.) :b4 colour illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v17500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Abbreviations, Quotations, and References -- tIntroduction -- t1: Wolfram and Polemic: Lohengrin and the Wartburgkrieg -- t2: Wolfram and Chronicles: Lohengrin and the Sächsische Weltchronik -- t3: Lohengrin’s Journey: Identity in Transition -- t4: Lohengrin’s Battles: Seeing and Hearing Identity -- t5: Lohengrin’s Farewell: Knowing Identity -- tConclusion -- tAppendix 1: Manuscripts -- tAppendix 2: Ottonian Germany in Recension A of the Sächsische Weltchronik: Herzog August Bibliothek Wolfenbüttel, Cod. Guelf. 23.8 Aug. 4° -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first monograph in English on the German Lohengrin, offering a new response to the challenges posed by the text.The tale of the mysterious knight carried across the water by a swan to the woman he saves and marries is one of the great narrative traditions of the Middle Ages. The version in the German Lohengrin (ca.1300) is perhaps the most striking. It captures the imagination with the appearance of the epic poet Wolfram von Eschenbach as narrator, the changing forms of the swan, and Lohengrin's appearance as a warrior alongside Saints Peter and Paul. In thepast, however, Lohengrin has been dismissed as an awkward amalgamation of earlier sources - partly due to more recent retellings of the material, such as Wagner's opera. This first monograph on Lohengrin in English presents a new response to the challenges the text poses. It is a study of how we read narrative across temporal distance, and at its heart lies the question: if a story is not held together by the chronological and causal links characteristic of modern narratives, how does it cohere? Alastair Matthews analyzes both the invocations of Wolfram that frame the text and the story of the Swan Knight that they enclose, arguing that Lohengrin is defined by a web of connections in which questions of identity and recognition are crucial, and thus that the themes at the core of the tale govern how it is told. Alastair Matthews, DPhil Oxford, is a Marie Curie ResearchFellow at the Centre for Medieval Literature, University of Southern Denmark.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismyMiddle High German, 1050-1500. 0aKnights and knighthood in literature. 0aSwan-knight (Legendary character). 4aGerman Literature. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aEnglish studies.  aGerman folklore.  aGerman medieval liteature.  aGerman middle ages.  aGerman studies.  aGermanic.  afolklore.  aliterature.  amedieval literature.  amiddle ages.  anarrative.  atales.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782048473?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97